---
import CaseStudy from "../layouts/CaseStudy.astro";
import TableItem from "../components/TableItem.astro";
import Divider from "../components/Divider.astro";
import Contents from "../components/Contents.astro";
import SubContents from "../components/SubContents.astro";
import { vocabForest } from "../data/projects.js";

import { MoveDown } from "@lucide/astro";

const sections = {
  overview: { id: "#overview", name: "Overview" },
  design_process: { id: "#design-process", name: "Design process" },
  problem_space: { id: "#problem-space", name: "Problem space" },
  explorations: { id: "#explorations", name: "Explorations" },
  wireframe_and_design_system: {
    id: "#wireframe-and-design-system",
    name: "Wireframe and design system",
  },
  final_design_and_insights: {
    id: "#final-design-and-insights",
    name: "Final design and insights",
  },
  dev_process: { id: "#dev-process", name: "Dev process" },
};
---

<CaseStudy
  image={vocabForest.image}
  title={vocabForest.title}
  links={vocabForest.links}
  tags={vocabForest.tags}
>
  <!-- Table of contents -->
  <Contents slot="TableOfContents">
    <a href={sections.overview.id}>{sections.overview.name}</a>
    <a href={sections.design_process.id}>{sections.design_process.name}</a>

    <!-- Design process toc -->
    <SubContents>
      <a href={sections.problem_space.id}>{sections.problem_space.name}</a>
      <a href={sections.explorations.id}>{sections.explorations.name}</a>
      <a href={sections.wireframe_and_design_system.id}
        >{sections.wireframe_and_design_system.name}</a
      >
      <a href={sections.final_design_and_insights.id}
        >{sections.final_design_and_insights.name}</a
      >
    </SubContents>

    <!-- Dev process toc -->
    <a href={sections.dev_process.id}>{sections.dev_process.name}</a>
  </Contents>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section>
    <h2 id={sections.overview.id}>{sections.overview.name}</h2>
    <p>
      Vocab Forest is a web app that allows users to search and save vocabulary
      cards into lists. Built using React and Supabase as its main technologies,
      this was a personal project that I worked on with a friend with the goal
      of learning more about full stack development.
    </p>
    <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:gap-2 gap-4 sm:justify-between pb-4">
      <TableItem item="Role">
        Full Stack Developer<br />
        UI/UX Designer
      </TableItem>
      <TableItem item="Team">
        Nadzmi Ag Thomas<br />
        Angela Ho
      </TableItem>
      <TableItem item="Timeline">
        March-April 2026<br />
        5 weeks
      </TableItem>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Divider />

  <!-- Design process -->
  <section>
    <h2 id={sections.design_process.id}>{sections.design_process.name}</h2>
    <a
      href={sections.dev_process.id}
      class="text-subtext cursor-pointer flex flex-row gap-0.5 items-center pb-4"
    >
      Skip to read about the Dev process
      <MoveDown size={16} stroke-width={1.7} />
    </a>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem space -->
  <section>
    <h3 id={sections.problem_space.id}>{sections.problem_space.name}</h3>
    <p>
      Why make Vocab Forest? Vocab Forest was created because I wanted a quick
      and simple way to save unfamiliar words and their definitions while
      reading. I found existing methods of recording vocabulary to be a hassle,
      for example:
    </p>
    <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:gap-2 gap-4 sm:justify-between pb-4">
      <TableItem item="Using pen and paper">
        <ol>
          <li>Interrupted my reading</li>
          <li>Was slow, especially for longer definitions</li>
          <li>And had no sorting mechanism, making review difficult</li>
        </ol>
      </TableItem>
      <TableItem item="Using spreadsheets">
        <ol>
          <li>
            Was tedious, having to copy-paste multiple times into the correct
            column & formatting not carrying over
          </li>
          <li>Not mobile-friendly</li>
        </ol>
      </TableItem>
      <TableItem item="Using dictionary sites">
        <ol>
          <li>
            A negative user-experience: being dictionary first meant that I had
            to navigate several times to find my saved definitions
          </li>
          <li>Cluttered with ads / unnecessary info</li>
        </ol>
      </TableItem>
    </div>
    <p>
      From these observations, I decided that Vocab Forest should be a
      lightweight and easy-to-use app. It should only centre one core
      functionality: search and save definitions for later review.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Explorations -->
  <section>
    <h3 id={sections.explorations.id}>{sections.explorations.name}</h3>
    <p>
      Having the core functionality in mind, my initial explorations focused on
      two main questions: what data to display, and how to display it. This was
      done through brainstorming and sketch sessions.
    </p>
    <p>
      I narrowed down the design to having a card gallery as the “main” view,
      and an expanded sidebar view on the left. I wanted this sidebar to include
      information that was important to me - definitions (including all
      variations), synonyms, antonyms, and a section for notes.
    </p>
  </section>
</CaseStudy>

<style>
  section {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: var(--font-weight-medium);
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    line-height: var(--text-xl--line-height);
    color: var(--color-text);
    padding-top: calc(var(--spacing) * 4);
    padding-bottom: calc(var(--spacing) * 2);
  }

  h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: var(--font-weight-medium);
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    line-height: var(--text-lg--line-height);
    color: var(--color-text);
    padding-top: calc(var(--spacing) * 4);
    padding-bottom: calc(var(--spacing) * 2);
  }

  p {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--text-base--line-height);
    padding-bottom: calc(var(--spacing) * 4)
  }

  ol {
    display: block;
    list-style-type: disc;
    padding-inline-start: 20px;
  }

  a:hover {
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  a {
    text-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
